{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566598"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:44:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:44:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18852"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.11,0.02,0.64,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79727"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65031"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11304"},{"type":"tags","id":"11305"},{"type":"tags","id":"11306"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27261"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79727"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student observes different patterns of behaviour during their clinical placement. They notice that some patients receive varying levels of attention and care that appear to be influenced by non-medical factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following scenarios best describes discrimination in a healthcare setting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Automatically scheduling older patients with multiple comorbidities for longer appointment times","Prioritising emergency cases in triage based on clinical need","Providing additional support services to patients with disabilities","Referring non-English speaking patients only to specific doctors","Offering gender-specific health screening programs"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferring non-English speaking patients only to specific doctors\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents discrimination as it restricts patient choice and access to healthcare based on language, potentially leading to delays in care and reduced quality of service. While having doctors who can communicate in different languages is valuable, automatically restricting patients to only these providers is discriminatory.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrioritising emergency cases in triage based on clinical need\u003C/strong\u003E - This is appropriate medical practice based on clinical urgency rather than discrimination\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutomatically scheduling older patients with multiple comorbidities for longer appointment times\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents reasonable accommodation for potentially complex care needs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding additional support services to patients with disabilities\u003C/strong\u003E - This is an example of appropriate accommodation to ensure equitable access to healthcare\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOffering gender-specific health screening programs\u003C/strong\u003E - This reflects evidence-based medical practice tailored to biological needs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers must ensure equal access and quality of care for all patients while making appropriate accommodations where medically indicated. Discrimination occurs when differences in treatment are based on non-medical factors and result in disadvantage or restricted access to healthcare services.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Discrimination in healthcare settings can occur based on protected characteristics including age, disability, gender, race, religion, and sexual orientation.","Healthcare providers have legal and ethical obligations to provide equitable care to all patients regardless of their background.","Discrimination can manifest as both direct (overt) and indirect (systemic) forms in healthcare delivery."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","Togioka BM, Duvivier D, Young E. Diversity and Discrimination in Health Care. [Updated 2024 May 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK568721/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65031"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65031"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T13:39:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T13:39:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79727"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":n